FROGS 5 DIALOGUE EVALUATION GUIDE
Companion to the WRITING GUIDE. Read both before writing any NPC dialogue.

The WRITING GUIDE establishes the prose rules -- what words earn their place, how to show
instead of state, how to write for the ear. This guide sits one level above those rules and
asks a different question: does the dialogue WORK AS HUMAN SPEECH? The WRITING GUIDE catches
bad sentences. This guide catches scenes where every sentence is clean and none of them sound
like a person actually talking.

The framework below is adapted from a breakdown of how dialogue fails in popular media --
specifically the pattern of technically functional lines that no real person would ever say.
The term for this failure is FAIRY TALE DIALOGUE.

=======================================================
I. WHAT FAIRY TALE DIALOGUE IS
=======================================================

Fairy tale dialogue is the simplification of a character to a caricature who speaks in one
repetitive, predictable dimension. Like characters in a fairy tale, every line is safe,
expected, and -- if spoken in the real world -- completely absurd.

The defining feature: the characters do not sound like people. They sound like ROLES. The
funny one is always funny. The blunt one is always blunt. The nervous one is always nervous.
Every line lands exactly where you expect it to, and no line surprises you, because no line
comes from a real human reaction -- it comes from a character sheet's one-word description.

In a fairy tale, this is fine. In a story that asks its audience to care about people in
danger, it is fatal. The audience cannot invest in a character who does not sound like a
person, no matter how high the stakes are supposed to be.

HOW TO SPOT IT: if you can predict what a character will say before they say it based solely
on their archetype -- the cautious one will caution, the brave one will rally, the comic
relief will quip -- the dialogue has collapsed into fairy tale mode.

=======================================================
II. THE THREE METRICS -- WHAT DIALOGUE HAS TO DO
=======================================================

All dialogue must satisfy three requirements simultaneously. Each one is necessary; none is
sufficient alone.

--- 1. PROPULSION ---
Dialogue must advance the story. It exposes information (context: why things are the way they
are) and drives action (plot: where the story goes next). Character speech is the most
efficient tool a story has for revealing what the audience needs to know and triggering what
happens next.

This is the easiest requirement to hit. The only constraint is the information that needs
expressing, and human language offers near-infinite ways to express any given piece of
information.

THE TEST: after this exchange, does the audience know something they didn't, or has
something changed that wasn't changed before? If neither, the dialogue is stalling.

--- 2. CHARACTERIZATION ---
Dialogue must sound like it comes from a specific person, not a plot-delivery device. It
should reflect voice, personality, history, and the character's relationship to whoever
they are talking to. This is what makes the journey -- the individual scenes -- worth
experiencing, not just the destination.

This is harder than propulsion because it requires filtering every line through a specific
character. But it is still a large target. There are many correct ways to give a character
a distinctive voice.

THE TEST: could this line be spoken by a different character in a different scene and still
work unchanged? If yes, it is not characterized -- it is plot wearing a character's name.
(This test is identical to WRITING GUIDE VII.5 because it IS the same principle.)

--- 3. BELIEVABILITY ---
Dialogue must sound like something a real person would actually say in that situation. Not
a cleaned-up, articulate, theatrically convenient version of what they might say -- the
actual messy, limited, half-formed thing a real human being would produce under those
specific circumstances.

This is the hardest requirement and the smallest target because real people are, frankly,
boring and reserved compared to fictional characters. Real people trail off, repeat
themselves, talk past each other, avoid the point, get stuck on the wrong detail, and
rarely produce a clean epigram on the first try. This mundanity is not a flaw to overcome
-- it is the raw material that makes dialogue land.

THE TEST: say the line out loud in the character's situation. Does it sound like something
a real person -- of that age, background, emotional state, and relationship to the
listener -- would actually say? Not "could theoretically say if they were very articulate
and had time to compose their thoughts," but WOULD say, right now, under pressure, without
a script.

=======================================================
III. THE ORDER OF OPERATIONS -- BELIEVABILITY FIRST
=======================================================

The three metrics are not created equal in difficulty.

Propulsion is the most flexible. Nearly infinite ways to get information across.
Characterization is moderately constrained. Many ways to voice a specific character.
Believability is the most strict. Severely limited by how people actually talk.

THE CRITICAL INSIGHT: because believability is the hardest target to hit, it must be the
FIRST filter applied to any dialogue -- not the last.

The fairy tale dialogue failure happens when writers work in the WRONG order:
  1. Start with propulsion (what does the audience need to know?)
  2. Add characterization (how can I make this sound like this character?)
  3. Treat believability as an afterthought (does this sound real? ...close enough)

By the time believability is considered, the line is already locked into a shape dictated
by information delivery and character voice, and there is no room left for it to also
sound human. The result: propulsive, characterized, completely absurd dialogue.

THE CORRECT ORDER:
  1. Start with believability (what would a real person actually say here?)
  2. Filter through characterization (what would THIS specific person say?)
  3. Ensure propulsion (does the scene still move forward?)

When believability comes first, the other two requirements are EASIER to achieve, not
harder -- because real human speech already contains character (people do not talk the same
way) and already moves situations forward (people talk to GET things, not to deliver
exposition). The hard work is done; the other two ride on top of it.

THE FROGS 5 APPLICATION: this maps directly onto existing rules. WRITING GUIDE IX.7 (the
Purpose Test) is a believability-first check -- "what does the SPEAKER get from saying
this?" is asking whether a real person would say this line for a real reason. CLAUDE.md
Rule 8 (every line needs a reason for the speaker) is the same principle from the
enforcement side. The order-of-operations framework is the WHY behind those rules: they
work because they force believability to be the first filter, not the last.

=======================================================
IV. THE OVERLAP PROBLEM -- WHY FAIRY TALE DIALOGUE IS TEMPTING
=======================================================

Propulsion and characterization are somewhat exclusive to each other. Getting to the point
(propulsion) and living in the moment (characterization) pull in opposite directions. The
overlap -- dialogue that is both efficient AND distinctive -- is already a surprisingly
small target to hit.

Fairy tale dialogue lives in this overlap. It IS propulsive and characterized. That is why
it feels like it works and why writers settle for it -- because hitting two out of three
requirements already took real effort.

But believability overlaps with BOTH of those targets only in a tiny sliver. Dialogue that
is propulsive, characterized, AND believable is an incredibly small window. This explains
why so much dialogue in popular media sounds wrong -- the target is genuinely hard, and
most writers are satisfied with two out of three.

THE UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH: fairy tale dialogue is not lazy writing. It is the result of real
effort applied in the wrong order. Acknowledging that the writers are TRYING -- and still
failing -- is what makes the order-of-operations correction so important. It is not about
trying harder. It is about trying DIFFERENTLY.

=======================================================
V. HOW TO BRAINSTORM BELIEVABLE DIALOGUE -- THE METHOD
=======================================================

When building a scene with dialogue, follow this sequence:

--- STEP 1: ESTABLISH WHAT THE CHARACTERS KNOW ---
Before writing a single line, map what each character in the scene knows and does not know
at that exact moment. Not what the AUDIENCE knows. Not what the WRITER knows. What each
individual character, with their specific history and information access, actually has in
their head right now.

Characters who know different things will naturally talk past each other, ask questions the
audience already knows the answer to, fixate on the wrong detail, or miss the point entirely.
This is not a flaw -- this IS believability.

--- STEP 2: ESTABLISH WHAT THE CHARACTERS FEEL ---
Given what they know and what they have just been through, what is their emotional state?
Not their archetype's default emotion. Their ACTUAL state, right now, given the specific
events of the last few hours or days.

A nine-year-old who has been dragged through a war zone does not engage in rational discourse.
They cry, or they shut down, or they cling to the nearest safe thing, or they lash out. The
emotional reality of the situation CONSTRAINS what dialogue is possible, and that constraint
is a gift -- it automatically eliminates the fairy tale options.

--- STEP 3: ESTABLISH WHAT EACH CHARACTER WANTS ---
Not what the scene needs them to want. What THEY want, as a person, in this moment. This
maps directly to WRITING GUIDE IX.7 (the Purpose Test): every line must serve the speaker's
want, not the audience's need.

A character's want in a scene is usually simple and personal: to feel safe, to be believed,
to not be alone, to understand what is happening, to make it stop. These small, human wants
produce dialogue that sounds like people -- because they ARE what people actually talk about
under pressure.

--- STEP 4: LET THE WANTS COLLIDE ---
Dialogue happens when characters with different knowledge, different emotional states, and
different wants try to talk to each other. The scene writes itself when these elements
conflict naturally -- which they almost always do, because real people are rarely on the
same page.

Do NOT choreograph the collision to land on a predetermined beat. Let the wants play out
and find where the scene naturally arrives. If the scene needs to end in a specific place
for plot reasons (propulsion), reverse-engineer the emotional path that would get real
people there -- do not force the characters to skip ahead to the destination.

--- STEP 5: CHECK PROPULSION LAST ---
After the believable, characterized dialogue exists, ask: does the scene move the story
forward? If yes, done. If not, adjust -- but adjust by changing the CIRCUMSTANCES, not the
dialogue. Give the characters a different piece of information, or put them in a slightly
different situation, so that their REAL reactions naturally produce the plot movement you
need. Never paste propulsive lines onto a believable scene -- that is how fairy tale
dialogue gets born.

=======================================================
VI. THE FAILURE MODES -- SPECIFIC PATTERNS TO CATCH
=======================================================

These are the recognizable shapes fairy tale dialogue takes. Each one is a symptom of
prioritizing propulsion or characterization over believability.

--- 1. THE HR EMPLOYEE ---
A character -- especially a child or someone under extreme duress -- speaks with the calm,
measured, complete-sentence diction of a corporate professional. Full clauses, no
interruptions, vocabulary beyond their plausible range. This happens when the writer needs
information delivered cleanly and forgets that stressed humans do not deliver information
cleanly.

THE FIX: stress the speaker. Interrupt them. Let them struggle with words. Let the
information come out messy and incomplete -- the audience will piece it together, and the
effort of piecing it together will make them more invested, not less.

--- 2. THE QUIP FACTORY ---
Every character gets one reliable comedic or dramatic note that they hit in every scene
regardless of context. The funny one quips during a crisis. The serious one scowls. The
nerd explains. Every line is a mic-drop, and none of them feel like conversation.

THE FIX: take the character's reliable note away for this scene. What does the funny
character say when nothing is funny? What does the nerd say when the explanation does not
help? Characters are most themselves when their default mode fails them.

--- 3. THE SYNCHRONIZED SWIM ---
Characters are weirdly on the same page, finish each other's sentences, immediately
understand metaphors and plans, and arrive at the same conclusion simultaneously. Real
people do not synchronize. They misunderstand, talk over each other, need things repeated,
and arrive at conclusions at different speeds.

THE FIX: let at least one character be behind. Let someone not get it. Let someone fixate
on the wrong part of what was just said. Disagreement and confusion are not obstacles to
good dialogue -- they ARE good dialogue.

--- 4. THE EXPOSITION PUPPET ---
A character says something no person would say out loud because the audience needs to hear
it. Recap dialogue, catch-up monologues, characters explaining things to people who already
know them. This is WRITING GUIDE IX.7's failure mode (the Purpose Test), but it is worth
restating here because it is the single most common symptom of propulsion-first writing.

THE FIX: if information needs to reach the audience and no character has a real reason to
say it out loud, do not force it into dialogue. Use action, environment, or a brief
narrated beat instead. Or find a character who genuinely DOES need to say it -- to someone
who genuinely does NOT know it -- and route it through that real exchange.

--- 5. THE SHAKESPEARE ---
A character -- especially a child, or anyone who should be inarticulate -- stands up and
delivers a perfectly structured, rhetorically polished speech. Complete with thesis
statement, supporting arguments, and a rousing conclusion. No real person talks like this,
especially not under pressure, and especially not children.

THE FIX: break the speech. Have someone interrupt. Have the speaker lose their thread. Let
the point come out in three frustrated half-sentences instead of one clean paragraph. The
messiness is not a loss of craft -- it IS the craft. Messy delivery that sounds real will
always hit harder than a polished speech that sounds fake.

--- 6. THE ARCHETYPE LOCK ---
Every character's lines are predictable based solely on their role. The cautious one always
cautions. The leader always rallies. The innocent one always asks naive questions. Characters
never break type, never surprise, never say something their archetype "wouldn't" say. This is
the core mechanism of fairy tale dialogue and the hardest one to catch, because each individual
line seems "in character" even though the cumulative effect is a cast of robots.

THE FIX: find ONE moment in the scene where a character says something their archetype would
not predict. The cautious one snaps. The leader admits they do not know. The tough one asks
for help. ONE break from type per scene is enough to shatter the fairy tale and remind the
audience these are people.

=======================================================
VII. THE AGE TEST -- CHILDREN ESPECIALLY
=======================================================

Children are the canary in the fairy tale dialogue coal mine. When dialogue sounds wrong, it
almost always sounds wrongest in children's mouths, because children have the smallest
vocabulary, the least emotional regulation, and the most limited rhetorical ability.

A nine-year-old:
  - Does not use words like "evil," "nasty," or "lies" in the abstract, evaluative way an
    adult would. They use concrete, immediate language: "He's bad," "She's lying," "I saw it."
  - Does not construct arguments. They make assertions and get frustrated when the assertions
    are not accepted.
  - Does not engage in rational discourse under stress. They cry, yell, shut down, cling, or
    run.
  - Talks in short bursts, not paragraphs. Interrupts. Gets interrupted. Loses their train of
    thought.
  - Fixates on one concrete detail instead of synthesizing the big picture. ("He locked the
    door" matters more to a scared nine-year-old than "he's trying to destroy the world.")

THE RULE: if a line sounds wrong in a child's mouth, it is probably wrong in an adult's mouth
too -- just less obviously. Children expose the problem because they have less range to hide
behind. Use child characters as a diagnostic: if the dialogue passes the child test, it will
almost certainly pass for adults.

THE FROGS 5 APPLICATION: many NPCs in this project are young, rural, uneducated, or under
extreme stress -- all conditions that constrain speech in the same ways childhood does. A
farmer under siege does not construct rhetoric. A teenager in a war zone does not deliver
exposition. Apply the age test broadly: if the character's circumstances would limit their
speech, let the speech BE limited.

=======================================================
VIII. THE DIALOGUE SELF-CHECK (run alongside the WRITING GUIDE's self-check)
=======================================================

This check runs BEFORE the WRITING GUIDE's Section VI pass. The WRITING GUIDE checks whether
the prose is clean. This check asks whether the dialogue is HUMAN.

1. ORDER-OF-OPERATIONS CHECK. Was believability the first filter? Or was the line written to
   deliver information first and then dressed up to sound like a person? If the latter, start
   over from what a real person would actually say.

2. PREDICTION CHECK. Can you predict this line based solely on the character's archetype? If
   yes, the line is fairy tale. Find the human reaction that the archetype would not predict.

3. SYNCHRONIZATION CHECK. Are the characters too much on the same page? Do they finish each
   other's thoughts, immediately understand each other, or arrive at the same conclusion at
   the same time? If yes, break the synchronization. Let someone misunderstand.

4. SAY-IT-OUT-LOUD CHECK. Say the line out loud, in character, in context. Does it sound like
   something a person would say? Not "could say" -- WOULD say, naturally, without a script.
   If you wince, the line fails.

5. AGE-AND-CIRCUMSTANCE CHECK. Is this character speaking beyond their plausible vocabulary,
   composure, or rhetorical ability given their age, education, emotional state, and the
   specific pressure of this moment? If yes, downgrade the line to what they can actually
   produce.

6. WANT CHECK. (Identical to WRITING GUIDE IX.7, restated here because it is the single most
   important believability test.) What does the SPEAKER get from saying this? If the only
   honest answer is "the audience needs this information," the line fails.

7. COLLISION CHECK. Do the characters in this scene have different knowledge, different
   emotional states, and different wants? If everyone is aligned, the scene will feel fake
   no matter how good the individual lines are. Introduce asymmetry.

=======================================================
IX. RELATIONSHIP TO EXISTING GUIDES
=======================================================

This guide does NOT replace any existing rule. It adds a LAYER that sits above the sentence-
level checks in the WRITING GUIDE and the enforcement gates in CLAUDE.md.

The hierarchy:
  1. THIS GUIDE asks: is this dialogue believable as human speech? (Scene-level check.)
  2. WRITING GUIDE Section IX asks: does each line serve the speaker's want, avoid the
     fingerprint patterns, and pass the camera test? (Line-level check.)
  3. WRITING GUIDE Sections VII-VIII ask: is the prose clean, spoken-ready, and free of AI
     tells? (Word-level check.)
  4. CLAUDE.md's Dialogue Audit Gate (G6) asks: has each rule been visibly checked before the
     draft goes in front of the GM? (Process-level check.)

Run them in this order. A line that passes the WRITING GUIDE's checks but fails this guide's
believability test is still fairy tale dialogue -- it is just well-written fairy tale dialogue.
The audience can tell the difference.
